  "text": "Six healthy adult men participated in the unweighting and gait analysis part of the study. The mean age of the subjects was 30 yr (range ϭ 22-42), mean height was 1.86 m (range ϭ 1.78 -1.98), and mean weight was 91.2 kg (range ϭ 76.2-108.4). All subjects were relatively active and had no known gait abnormalities. A spring weighing scale was placed under each subject, and the chamber pressures needed to generate specific levels of unloading (100, 60, and 20% bodyweight) were determined. The scale was then removed and subjects walked at 3 mph (1.34 m/s) and ran at 6 mph (2.68 m/s) while the chamber pressure was adjusted to achieve each of the three BW conditions. Conditions were performed in randomized order for all subjects. It was previously demonstrated that walking kinematics rapidly adapt to simulated reductions in gravity [CITATION_1] ; consequently, all data were acquired after 1 min of exercise to allow subjects time to acclimatize to the reduced gravity.",
